# pricelevel-pricetime.patch
#
# Price-time-priority fix for the `pricelevel` crate (pricelevel = "0.7",
# pinned at 0.7.0), the dependency that OrderBook-rs (joaquinbejar/OrderBook-rs)
# does its actual per-level matching in. Applied by build.sh with `git apply
# -p1` to a freshly-extracted, pristine pricelevel-0.7.0 source tree (vendored
# build-locally under wrapper/pricelevel-patched/, git-ignored), so the patched
# crate replaces the crates.io copy via the wrapper's [patch.crates-io].
#
# Bug (filed upstream as https://github.com/joaquinbejar/OrderBook-rs/issues/88;
# see CORRECTNESS_FINDINGS.md): in PriceLevel::match_order a partially
# filled head order has its residual re-queued with `self.orders.push(...)`,
# which sends it to the TAIL of the level's FIFO. Any same-price order that
# arrived after the original maker is then matched ahead of the maker's
# remainder on the next trade at that price — a price-time-priority violation.
# Total resting quantity at the level is unchanged; only the maker_order_id of
# subsequent same-price fills is wrong, which fails the benchmark report-stream
# hash on all five scenarios.
#
# Fix (engine-source, not an adapter workaround): give OrderQueue a deque-like
# backing (Mutex<VecDeque<Id>> instead of the tail-only SegQueue<Id>) and add a
# push_front primitive, then re-queue the partial-fill residual at the FRONT
# (level.rs match_order partial-fill arm) so the head keeps its time priority.
# The unrelated tail push at level.rs update_order (explicit modify) is left as
# push — modify-to-back is correct. pricelevel's own 144 price_level unit tests
# pass unchanged.
#
# Reference: https://github.com/flash1-dev/matching-engine-benchmark
